This problem describes a propagation process where the time taken for a color to reach a cell is related to the shortest distance (Manhattan distance, since movement is restricted to adjacent cells) from any source of that color.

If a cell $(r, c)$ is reached by color $C_i$ originating at source $S_i = (r_i, c_i)$ at time $t_i$, then $t_i = |r - r_i| + |c - c_i|$.
Since multiple colors might reach $(r, c)$, the cell will eventually adopt the color $C_j$ such that $t_j$ is minimized, and among those achieving the minimum time, it adopts the color with the maximum value.

